Headlines.Author: Steven Russolillo
Headlines.Headline: Morning MarketBeat: Google, Microsoft Illustrate Tech’s Struggles

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:MARKET SNAP: At 5:00 a.m. ET, S&P 500 futures down 0.2%. Treasury yields lower. Nymex down at $92.01; gold lower 0.5% at $1,732.99. In Europe, FTSE 100 down 0.1%, DAX down 0.3% and CAC 40 down 0.4%. In Asia, Nikkei 225 up 0.2% and Hang Seng up 0.2%.Overnight action: Europe agrees on bank supervisor; Volvo announces new CEO; Microsoft's profit falls 22%.Watch for: September existing home sales (10:00 a.m. Eastern Time): Seen falling 1.5% after rising 7.8% in August. In Europe, the two-day EU summit concludes. General Electric, McDonald's and Honeywell are among companies reporting quarterly results.For more MarketBeat and other streaming markets coverage from The Wall Street Journal, point your mobile browser to wsj.com/marketspulse.The Breakfast BriefingGoogle’s earnings drubbing wasn’t an anomaly.While the Internet company’s early quarterly release drew plenty of scrutiny, Google's lackluster results magnified the underlying trouble plaguing the tech sector.Google’s third-quarter profit missed analysts’ expectations by a wide margin, and the company also warned that a growing shift toward mobile searches could be hitting its top line.Disappointing tech results this week have become commonplace. From IBM and Intel, to Google and Microsoft, tech titans have struggled to grow profits and revenues at a pace that lives up to Wall Street’s expectations.Google’s shares dropped 8% yesterday, rattling the tech world, while Microsoft’s disappointing report after the closing bell added to the gloomy sentiment. Microsoft’s results were hurt by weak PC demand and slowing growth for business software, which has historically been a cash cow for the company. Shares fell 1.6% in off-hours trading.The Nasdaq Comp dropped 1% in yesterday’s trading, outpacing both the Dow and the S&P 500. It was the tech-heavy index’s seventh drop of the last 10 trading days.Meanwhile, the S&P 500’s tech sector is down 5.6% over the past month, by far the worst performer of the index’s 10 large-cap sectors.Some of that weakness can be attributed to the biggest company on the planet, Apple Inc. Shares are down 9.9% from the record high hit in September, and have recently bounced in and out of correction territory, considered at least a 10% decline from a peak to trough.For now, though, the Dow and S&P 500 are clinging to gains of about 1% this month. The Nasdaq Comp has felt the brunt of tech’s struggles, dropping 1.4% in October.Utilities and health-care stocks have been the S&P 500's best performers over the last month, while tech, telecom and energy have lagged the most, indicating more defensive posturing among investors.Major stock indexes sit within shouting distance of their highest levels since 2007, and record highs are not far away. But without tech participating, it will be tough for the market to reclaim those milestones anytime soon.Morning MarketBeat Daily Factoid: On this day in 1987, the Dow plunged 508 points, or 22.6%, in a single day of trading. #text: Ingersoll-Rand PLC

raised its second-quarter targets as stronger-than-expected demand and cost controls boosted margins. Meanwhile, the industrial conglomerate plans to sell its European refrigerated display case business and is evaluating proposals as it aims to shed noncore business.
